# {{.app_name}} — Development Rules

This file is read by Claude / Cursor before generating code. Treat it as
binding. The CI validator enforces most of it; reviewers enforce the rest.

## Architecture (read first)

Before changing anything Lakebase-related, read:
- `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`
- `docs/RUNBOOK.md`
- `docs/DATA_CLASSIFICATION.md`

## Auth

- **OBO** (`x-forwarded-access-token`) for every user-facing read from Unity Catalog.
- **SP** for Lakebase writes, background tasks, and audit logging.
- Pick clients via `server/auth/config.py` helpers; never construct
  `WorkspaceClient` ad hoc.
- `DATABRICKS_HOST` may arrive without `https://` — `get_workspace_host()`
  normalises it. Always go through that helper.

## Lakebase

- Connection pool with OAuth token refresh every 45 min lives in
  `server/db/lakebase.py`. Do not bypass it.
- `asyncpg` with `ssl="require"`.
- Schema changes go through **Alembic migrations**. Never run manual
  `ALTER TABLE` against prod. Every migration MUST implement `downgrade()`
  — the validator will reject empty `pass` downgrades.
- Read `PGHOST` / `PGPORT` / `PGDATABASE` / `PGUSER` from env — they are
  injected by the `lakebase_db` resource binding in `databricks.yml`.
- For *cross-app* reads, request access to the `shared_ref` DB; do not
  duplicate reference data into your own DB.

## Data classification (binding)

- **Sensitive data (PHI/PII/regulated) stays in UC and is read via OBO.**
- Lakebase is for app state, derived data, reference data, write-back of
  user actions.
- If you genuinely need to cache sensitive data in Lakebase, see
  `docs/DATA_CLASSIFICATION.md` — you need a SQL view filter, server-side
  enforcement, and a data-steward sign-off in the PR.

## Permissions

- Declare every UC schema/table and every Lakebase schema/table your app
  needs in `permissions.yaml`. The `apply_grants.py` script runs after each
  deploy and grants them to the app SP.
- Do not ask an admin to grant things manually — that means the YAML is
  wrong. Fix the YAML, redeploy.

## Logging

- `AuditLoggerMiddleware` auto-captures every request as JSON. Do not add
  manual `print`/`logger.info` per route — it duplicates audit lines.
- Logs flow to stdout, then to the workspace `logs-sink` pipeline, which
  lands them in `{{.audit_catalog}}.audit.app_events`.
- Add app-specific fields by wrapping a request handler with your own log
  emit, not by modifying the middleware.

## Environment / deployment

- **The only deploy path is GitHub Actions** (`.github/workflows/deploy.yml`).
  No manual `databricks bundle deploy` from laptops, no UI uploads, no
  "click restart". Bypassing the pipeline skips migrations, grants, and
  the smoke test.
- All environment-specific values live in `databricks.yml` under
  `variables` / `targets`. The validator blocks PRs that hardcode a
  catalog name, workspace URL, or token.
- `app.yaml` must bind `0.0.0.0:8000`. Validator enforces.

## Tests

- Add a smoke test under `tests/` for any new route that touches
  Lakebase. The PR-branch CI is the right time to catch breakage.

## When in doubt

Open `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`, then ask Sahil or Juliana in
`#hss-app-platform`. Do not invent a new pattern silently.
